initial_story: bias triangles represent features in stability diagrams of quantum dot (qd)devices, whose occurrence and property analysis are crucial indicators for spinphysics. nevertheless, challenges associated with quality and availability ofdata as well as the subtlety of physical phenomena of interest have hindered anautomatic and bespoke analysis framework, often still relying (in part) onhuman labelling and verification. we introduce a feature extraction frameworkfor bias triangles, built from unsupervised, segmentation-based computer visionmethods, which facilitates the direct identification and quantification ofphysical properties of the former. thereby, the need for human input or largetraining datasets to inform supervised learning approaches is circumvented,while additionally enabling the automation of pixelwise shape and featurelabeling. in particular, we demonstrate that pauli spin blockade (psb)detection can be conducted effectively, efficiently and without any trainingdata as a direct result of this approach.

In the field of quantum computing, understanding the behavior of quantum bits (qubits) is crucial. A key component of this understanding comes from the analysis of stability diagrams of quantum dot devices. In these diagrams, certain features known as "stability triangles" hold important information about the spin physics of the system. However, extracting this information has proven to be challenging due to issues with data quality and availability, as well as the subtle and complex nature of the physical phenomena being studied.

To address this issue, we have developed a new feature extraction framework for stability triangles. This framework utilizes unsupervised, segmentation-based computer vision techniques to directly identify and quantify the physical properties of stability triangles. This approach eliminates the need for large training datasets and human input to inform supervised learning methods.

One of the key benefits of this framework is its ability to detect and analyze Pauli spin blockade (PSB) without the need for any training data. This is a crucial aspect of spin physics, as PSB plays a significant role in the behavior of qubits. With this new framework, we are able to effectively and efficiently detect and analyze PSB, leading to a better understanding of the stability and behavior of quantum dot devices. This is a major step forward in the development of reliable and stable quantum computers.

In the world of materials science, the behavior of two-dimensional materials holds the key to unlocking new technologies. A crucial aspect of understanding these materials comes from the analysis of stability maps in twistronics. Within these maps, distinct features known as "moiré triangles" contain valuable information about the electronic properties of the system. However, extracting this information has been difficult due to issues with data accuracy and complexity of the physical phenomena involved.

To tackle this problem, we have developed a new feature extraction framework for moiré triangles. This framework utilizes unsupervised, segmentation-based image processing techniques to directly identify and quantify the physical properties of moiré triangles. This method does not require large training datasets or human input to guide supervised learning algorithms.

One of the major advantages of this framework is its ability to detect and analyze moiré-induced flat bands (MIFB) without the need for any training data. MIFB plays a critical role in the electronic properties of 2D materials, and this new framework allows us to effectively and efficiently detect and analyze MIFB. This leads to a better understanding of the stability and behavior of these materials, paving the way for the development of reliable and high-performance electronics based on 2D materials. This is a significant advancement in the pursuit of next-generation technology.
